// =====================================================================
//  mdp.props   --   properties for bus_stop_mdp.nm
// =====================================================================
//  In an MDP, Pmin/Pmax and Rmin/Rmax quantify over ALL policies, so they
//  bracket what any scheduling strategy can achieve. The gap between min
//  and max is the "value of control" -- how much the dispatch decision
//  actually matters. The horizon terminal is  t = NSLOTS.
//  Reward "waiting" is in PERSON-SLOTS; multiply results by dt (=0.25) to
//  get person-minutes.
// =====================================================================

// (1) Best achievable: minimum expected total waiting (person-slots) over
//     the horizon, under the OPTIMAL holding policy.
R{"waiting"}min=? [ F t=NSLOTS ]

// (2) Worst case: maximum expected waiting under the worst policy.
//     (1) and (2) together show how much the holding decision matters.
R{"waiting"}max=? [ F t=NSLOTS ]

// (3) Can some policy keep the queue at/below 25 throughout the horizon?
Pmax=? [ (n<=25) U (t=NSLOTS) ]

// (4) Guaranteed (worst-case) probability of staying at/below 25.
Pmin=? [ (n<=25) U (t=NSLOTS) ]

// (5) Strategy synthesis: export the optimal policy for (1):
//     prism bus_stop_mdp.nm mdp.props -prop 1 -exportstrat strat.txt
//     The exported strategy says, in each state, whether to hold or depart.

// ---- BASELINE COMPARISON ------------------------------------------
//  To compare the optimal policy against a fixed "always depart" rule,
//  comment out the [hold] command in bus_stop_mdp.nm and re-run (1):
//  with only one choice the MDP becomes deterministic and Rmin = Rmax =
//  the always-depart cost. Report optimal vs always-depart as the
//  "value of control".
